class="comment-text"> <span
class="date">Mon 21st Nov 2011 at 6:04 am</span><p>The &#8220;Wire&#8221; is perhaps the best written TV show ever.  And, this, in my opinion, is the best blog post ever written on the stark reality of building software inside and outside of companies or as a contractor.  It is especially relevant today, when everyone and their mother has an idea and a little cash to build their million dollar app.  I had an experience with a guy in South Carolina who exhibited the same behaviors as you described to a T (<a
onclick="javascript:pageTracker._trackPageview('/outgoing/www.webiphany.com/2011/10/18/to-all-the-entrepreneurs-outside-of-silicon-valley-ny-and-boston/');"  href="http://www.webiphany.com/2011/10/18/to-all-the-entrepreneurs-outside-of-silicon-valley-ny-and-boston/" rel="nofollow">http://www.webiphany.com/2011/10/18/to-all-the-entrepreneurs-outside-of-silicon-valley-ny-and-boston/</a>).  From first glance he looked like a guy who was willing to put something at stake (a considerable amount of his own money), and someone that knew the industry he planned to disrupt.  When I started asking about process, and vision, however, all the things you described, he blew up on me by the third phone call.  I cannot more strongly echo your point to &#8220;talk about happy things.&#8221;  People that are unwilling to talk about the happy things are the people that you can never succeed at working with, no matter how long you talk about processes.  Beautiful post.</p> <span
